 and excluded even from democratic communities, though their legal status has fundamentally changed since the end of World War Two. Usually drawing upon Hannah Arendt and Giorgio Agamben, they are located outside of political spaces and therefore at the margin of the world. Yet Julia Schulze Wessel shows: By being marginal characters, refugees question, violate and transcend borders, thus challenging democratic orders in their own specific way. Marching through the border area of Europe, they also point out the limitations of law and move into the center of current political debates.  afunded by VG-Wort (7601-2016)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aBorder crossing. 0aEmigration and immigrationxPolitical aspects. 0aPolitical refugees. 0aRefugeesxPolitical aspects. 4aFlucht. 4aFlüchtlinge. 4aFlüchtlingsforschung. 4aFlüchtlingspolitik. 4aGeflüchtete. 4aGiorgio Agamben. 4aGrenze. 4aHannah Arendt. 4aMigration. 4aPolitik. 4aPolitische Philosophie. 4aPolitische Soziologie. 4aPolitische Theorie. 4aSoziologie. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aBorder.  aFleeing.  aGiorgio Agamben.  aHannah Arendt.  aMigration.  aPolitical Philosophy.  aPolitical Sociology.  aPolitical Theory.  aPolitics.  aRefugee Policy.  aRefugee Studies.  aRefugees.  aSociology.2 aVG-Wort (7601-2016)efunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2017z978311071954308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2017z9783110548242oZDB-23-DSW40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783839437568zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/97838